# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oak:unit-284
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "UK region: why is the Lake District a national park?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the Lake District as a UK National Park. Pupils learn about its landscape, weather and climate, how people live and work there, and the pressures on the environment caused by visitors and land use."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit deepens pupils’ understanding of how people live, work and interact with distinctive UK landscapes through the study of the Lake District. Its placement supports progression from land use and physical geography, and meets the National Curriculum’s expectation to study a UK region.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of what a mountain is and what a lake is.
Familiarity with the physical and human landscape of the UK.
Some experience of using and annotating OS maps.""" ;
  curric:id "284"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.347889Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-mountains-volcanoes-and-earthquakes ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-the-uk-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

oak:unit-299
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Around the world in 80 days: what have we learnt about our world?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit revisits key geographical themes through a global journey. Pupils explore news stories, regional features and environmental issues across all continents, using maps, data and fieldwork skills to reflect on what it means to think like a geographer."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit brings together pupils’ geographical knowledge and skills through a continent-by-continent review of key concepts and themes. Its placement at the end of Year 6 provides a meaningful opportunity to reflect on the role of geography in understanding people, places and problems. Pupils apply map and data skills, revisit physical and human features, and explore contemporary issues such as climate, resources and tourism. This final unit consolidates prior learning and encourages pupils to leave primary school with curiosity, confidence and a global perspective.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of places and geographical themes covered in KS2.
Experience of geographical enquiry, mapwork, fieldwork, critical thinking and use of a wide range of sources of information.""" ;
  curric:id "299"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.348944Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-diversity .

oak:unit-286
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Europe: what is it like to live in northern Italy?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores northern Italy through its landscapes, transport, cities and villages. Pupils learn about everyday life and tourism in the region, and compare it with their own local area using maps, images and geographical vocabulary."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to a region in a European country, as required by the National Curriculum, through a focused study of northern Italy. It builds on pupils’ understanding of the UK and wider Europe by enabling meaningful comparison between physical and human features, ways of life, and patterns of land use. Its placement follows regional study of the Lake District and a broader overview of Europe, giving pupils the knowledge and vocabulary they need to explore cultural and environmental similarities and differences at a regional scale.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge of global geography and the use of atlases to locate places.
Knowledge of the local region.
Some knowledge of using Google Earth, aerial photographs, maps, and other sources of geographical information to investigate places.""" ;
  curric:id "286"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.349468Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-europe-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

oak:unit-283
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Mountains and volcanoes: what, where and why?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces mountains and volcanoes, how they form, and what they’re like. Pupils study peaks in the UK and around the world, learn about volcanic eruptions, and explore how these features affect the lives of people who live nearby."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds pupils’ understanding of physical geography by introducing mountain and volcanic landscapes and how they form. Its placement supports progression from rivers and climate, helping pupils connect physical processes with real places and their human impacts.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the location of the four constituent nations of the UK.
Knowledge of the location of the seven continents and five oceans.
Map skills: four figure grid references, the importance of symbols on an OS map and the use of a key.
Understanding that there are similarities and differences in the physical and human geography of diverse localities.""" ;
  curric:id "283"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.349990Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-mountains-volcanoes-and-earthquakes ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-293
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Sustainable world: does it matter how we live?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces sustainability by exploring how human choices affect the environment. Pupils learn about energy use, food waste, biodiversity and urban living, and consider how individuals and communities can work towards a more sustainable future."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit brings together key ideas from across Year 5 to help pupils explore how our lives affect the planet and what can be done in response. Its placement encourages reflection on prior learning about forests, energy and climate, while developing a broader understanding of sustainability. Pupils learn to evaluate different human behaviours and consider positive changes individuals and communities can make.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some understanding of natural resources and energy.
Some knowledge of reasons why these are not distributed equally or fairly across the world.""" ;
  curric:id "293"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.352732Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change .

oak:unit-278
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Rivers: what's special about them?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores how rivers change the land as they flow. Pupils learn about the journey of a river from source to mouth, the effects of flooding, and what makes rivers important. They compare rivers in the UK, Europe and other parts of the world."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ learning about the water cycle and land use by focusing on rivers and their role in shaping the land. Its placement helps pupils understand how rivers work, why they matter, and how they affect people and places in the UK and beyond.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of what a river is and does (flows from high to low), basic river vocabulary.
Experience of having visited a local river or waterway and understanding of the water cycle.""" ;
  curric:id "278"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.407874Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-281
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local area: how is it changing?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupils’ fieldwork skills through an investigation of change in the local area. Pupils observe, measure, map and record evidence of change, gather local views, and begin to consider how places evolve over time."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit places fieldwork at the centre of pupils’ learning, giving them the tools to investigate real change in their local area. Its position builds on earlier work on settlements and mapping, and prepares pupils to ask questions, gather evidence and draw conclusions as geographers.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some experience of carrying out local area fieldwork.
Awareness of the key human and physical features in their locale.
Overview and understanding of settlements.
Some familiarity with historical and present OS maps.""" ;
  curric:id "281"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.408392Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-human-processes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-292
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Energy: how do we power the world?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores how energy is produced and used, and how this links to climate change. Pupils compare renewable and non-renewable sources, consider how energy use can be reduced, and evaluate different responses to the world’s growing energy demands."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit gives pupils the knowledge and tools to understand how our use of energy affects the planet. Its placement builds on earlier units about natural resources and the Amazon, encouraging pupils to connect energy production with environmental change. Pupils compare renewable and non-renewable sources, explore the causes and consequences of energy choices, and consider how individuals, communities and governments can respond to the energy challenge. This prepares them to think critically and constructively in the final sustainability-focused unit.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of natural resources.
Some experience of using a wide range of resources to investigate geographical issues.
Some experience of thinking about creative solutions to social and economic problems.""" ;
  curric:id "292"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.414866Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-interconnection .

oak:unit-295
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Natural resources: what are they, where are they found, why are they important?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces natural resources, including food, water, minerals and energy. Pupils explore where different resources are found, how they are used, and the effects of this use on people and the environment."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit gives pupils a broad understanding of natural resources and how they are used across the world. Its placement builds on prior learning about forests and prepares pupils to think more critically about sustainability and human impact. Pupils learn to distinguish between renewable and non-renewable resources, explore patterns of production and consumption, and consider the environmental and social consequences of resource use. This lays the groundwork for deeper enquiry into ecosystems, energy, and sustainable living in later units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge about the water cycle.
Some experience of investigating a natural resource, such as trees or woods, in the local area.""" ;
  curric:id "295"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.422537Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-interconnection .

oak:unit-291
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "South America: why does the Amazon matter?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the Amazon rainforest as a region in South America. Pupils learn about its location, climate and biodiversity, investigate how people live and work there, and consider the global importance of protecting tropical rainforests."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit fulfils the National Curriculum requirement to study a region in South America through an in-depth focus on the Amazon rainforest. Its placement builds on pupils’ earlier learning about physical geography, biomes and natural resources, while deepening understanding of global interdependence. Pupils explore the Amazon’s features, biodiversity and human geography, and consider how land use choices affect both people and planet. This prepares them to reflect critically on environmental change and sustainability in the final units of the year.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the location of South America, and its diverse range of people and landscapes.
Knowledge of the global distribution of climate zones and biomes, the importance of rainforests and the need to protect them from over-exploitation.""" ;
  curric:id "291"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.425634Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-americas-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-diversity ,
    oak:thread-interconnection .

oak:unit-298
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Global trade: how do we get our stuff?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores global trade and how goods are produced, transported and consumed around the world. Pupils investigate imports, exports, supply chains and the role of ethical trading in shaping how we access everyday items."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils’ understanding of global interdependence by exploring how goods are produced and traded. Its placement builds on earlier work on food systems and energy use, enabling pupils to examine how natural resources, transport and human decisions shape what we buy and use. Pupils explore trade routes, supply chains, and ethical issues, and begin to reflect on the economic and environmental consequences of global trade. This prepares them to think critically about fairness, sustainability and the human impact of everyday choices.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the diversity of physical and human geography at a global scale.
Knowledge of the historic and contemporary movement of goods, people and ideas, including some aspects of international trade.""" ;
  curric:id "298"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.465177Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-human-processes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-282
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The UK: who are we?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the UK’s regions, population and global links. Pupils learn about counties, migration and movement within and beyond the UK, and consider how the population is changing and what this means for the people and places that make up the UK today."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ earlier learning about the UK by focusing on how people shape places. Its placement introduces human geography themes of population, movement and identity, supporting pupils to explore diversity within and beyond the UK and reflect on how the UK is changing.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils need to have a geographical understanding of the human and physical landscape of the UK.
Some understanding about the factors that contribute to settlement.""" ;
  curric:id "282"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.470911Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-the-uk-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-diversity ,
    oak:thread-interconnection .

oak:unit-279
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Climate zones: what are they and why do they matter?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces climate zones around the world. Pupils use maps and climate data to spot patterns, compare environments, and explore how plants and animals adapt to different conditions. The unit also introduces climate change."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ understanding of weather and places by exploring how climate differs around the world. Its placement supports pupils to spot patterns, connect climate with the natural world, and begin to think about how the climate is changing.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the location of the hot and cold areas of the world.
Be familiar with the terms ‘Equator’ and ‘Polar Regions’, and know their location.
Know the difference between weather and climate.""" ;
  curric:id "279"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.479794Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change .

oak:unit-297
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Coasts: what happens where the land meets the sea?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores how coastal landscapes form and change. Pupils learn about erosion, habitats and human activity at the coast, and investigate how coastal environments are used, protected and managed in the face of ongoing change."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ knowledge of physical processes such as rivers and weathering by focusing on how the coastline is shaped and reshaped over time. Its placement supports pupils to apply map skills and understand how people interact with changing environments. Pupils explore erosion, defence strategies, tourism and ecosystems, and begin to consider how climate change and human decisions affect coastal places. This prepares them to evaluate geographical change and sustainability in the wider world.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Able to identify some key geographical features of a coast.
Some experience of a coastal location through first-hand experience.""" ;
  curric:id "297"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.490050Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-processes ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-the-uk-and-regions .

oak:unit-296
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Farms and factories: where does our food come from?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores how food is produced and distributed, both locally and globally. Pupils investigate where different foods come from, how diets are changing, and what environmental and social factors shape food production and supply."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ earlier learning about natural resources and trade by exploring food as a global system. Its placement enables pupils to connect physical and human geography by considering how land, climate, technology and economics influence what we eat. Pupils explore the journey from farm to factory to table, investigate food miles and supply chains, and begin to evaluate the impact of food production on people and the planet. This prepares them to think critically about sustainability, equity and future food challenges.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of farming in the UK.
Knowledge of the impact of climate zones and vegetation belts on what crops can be grown globally.
Skills in using a range of geographical resources to investigate geographical questions.""" ;
  curric:id "296"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.522466Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-human-processes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change .

oak:unit-276
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Land use: how diverse are local and UK landscapes?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores how land is used in the local area and across the UK. Pupils investigate human and physical features, farming, land use types and change, using aerial photos, maps and grid references to describe and compare landscapes."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ knowledge of their local area and UK geography by introducing how land is used and how it changes over time. Its placement supports progression from identifying features to analysing how human and physical processes shape landscapes at different scales.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some experience of map work and fieldwork in the local area.
Able to interpret a map key and aerial images using geographical vocabulary.""" ;
  curric:id "276"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.626866Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-human-processes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-277
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The water cycle: why is it important?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces the water cycle and explores how water moves through natural and built environments. Pupils investigate how water is used, supplied and owned, and consider how access to water differs in the UK and around the world."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to the water cycle as a key geographical process, building on their understanding of weather and rivers. Its placement encourages thinking about water as a global system and resource, supporting future study of sustainability and environmental change.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils will have familiarity with weather and its features, and with various types of water features locally and globally, from ponds to oceans.""" ;
  curric:id "277"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.640096Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-280
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Settlements: where do people live and why?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores different types of settlements, from villages to cities. Pupils learn about settlement features, growth and location, and use their local area to understand how places change. They apply what they’ve learned by designing a new settlement."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ knowledge of land use and physical features by focusing on where people live and why. Its placement helps pupils connect human geography to the places they know, while preparing them to explore change, planning and sustainability in later units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the local area and UK.
Experience of using aerial photographs and a range of maps to investigate the geographical features of places.""" ;
  curric:id "280"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.669179Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-human-processes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-289
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Earthquakes: how do they change the world?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the causes and effects of earthquakes. Pupils learn where and why they occur, how they are measured, and what can be done to prepare for and respond to them. Case studies include Japan (2011) and Turkey (2023)."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils’ understanding of Earth’s structure and tectonic activity by focusing on earthquakes and their impacts. Its placement builds on earlier physical geography units such as rivers, mountains and coasts, and prepares pupils to engage with risk and resilience. Pupils explore where earthquakes happen and why, how people respond, and what shapes the severity of impacts. By connecting physical processes to real-life events, the unit encourages critical thinking, empathy and an understanding of how geography affects lives around the world.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the structure of Earth.
Experience using a range of resources to investigate physical geography processes and their impact on people and environments.""" ;
  curric:id "289"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.714893Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-mountains-volcanoes-and-earthquakes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-290
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "North and South America: how diverse are their places and landscapes?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces the continents of North and South America through their physical and human features. Pupils explore climate, land use, and economic activity across different regions, and plan a journey that connects a range of contrasting places."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit extends pupils’ locational and place knowledge beyond Europe by focusing on the diversity of North and South America. Its placement builds on prior regional studies and prepares pupils to compare places at a larger scale. Pupils develop their ability to interpret climate data, physical features and patterns of land use, while also deepening their understanding of how people live and work in different environments. This broad foundation supports later learning about global ecosystems, interdependence and sustainability.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the location of the continents.
Knowledge of the diversity of physical and human geography at a continental scale.""" ;
  curric:id "290"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.715900Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-americas-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

oak:unit-294
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Time zones: can we time travel on planet Earth?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the relationship between the Earth's rotation, day and night, and time zones. Pupils learn how longitude affects time, investigate the International Date Line, and consider what happens when we travel across the globe."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils’ understanding of the Earth as a connected system by exploring how time is linked to place. Its placement introduces global concepts of longitude, rotation and time zones, deepening spatial thinking and building on earlier work in map skills, continents and climate. Pupils also begin to consider how geography influences human activity, such as travel and communication, preparing them for more complex global systems studied later in the year.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of how day and night are created by the rotation of the globe in relation to the sun, and that different time zones exist.""" ;
  curric:id "294"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.716438Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-earth-geometry .

oak:unit-288
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local and global: why are trees and forests important?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the importance of trees and forests at local, national and global scales. Pupils investigate the benefits of trees, map forest change over time, and plan action in response to environmental change in their own local area."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces key environmental geography concepts through a study of trees and forests. Its placement at the start of Year 5 connects local fieldwork with global understanding, enabling pupils to link observable features in their own area with patterns of change across the UK and the world. The unit deepens map and data interpretation skills while preparing pupils to engage with sustainability, ecosystems and land use in future units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge and understanding of their local area through fieldwork.
Understand what a tree is and that there are different types of tree.
Able to interpret patterns of land use on OS maps and have some experience of using Grid References.""" ;
  curric:id "288"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.716932Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change .

oak:unit-287
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local area: what needs changing?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupils’ fieldwork and enquiry skills through a local investigation into change. Pupils use maps, tools and data to explore how their area is changing, collect and present information, and reflect on possible changes in the future."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit gives pupils the opportunity to act as geographers through purposeful fieldwork. It builds on earlier mapping and local study units, and follows regional and European comparisons, encouraging pupils to apply their skills to real-world questions in a familiar context. Its placement near the end of the year supports reflection, allowing pupils to collect, present and evaluate evidence about local change. Through this, they develop confidence in fieldwork methods, geographical communication and decision-making.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Experience of fieldwork in the local area to investigate change in the locality.
Some knowledge of how their local area has changed over time.
Experience of learning about change and patterns of land use.
Some knowledge of how this can impact on and be affected by the people who live and work and visit in a place.""" ;
  curric:id "287"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.717424Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change .

oak:unit-3854
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fieldwork: how can we investigate the sustainability of our school?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the fieldwork enquiry process. Each lesson guides pupils through a stage of a fieldwork enquiry to help them investigate the sustainability of their school."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have learned about sustainability and the need to conserve natural resources in earlier Year 5 units. This prior knowledge provides a foundation for considering the sustainability of their own school. Fieldwork is an essential part of geographical enquiry, and while pupils have undertaken fieldwork in previous units, this is a good stage to explore the fieldwork enquiry process in greater depth.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """An understanding of the term sustainability.
Knowledge and experience of using maps and aerial images.""" ;
  curric:id "3854"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.717973Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 .

oak:unit-285
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Europe: how diverse are its landscapes and places?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces Europe as a continent of many countries, climates and landscapes. Pupils use maps to locate countries and cities, explore physical and human features, and consider how people live, travel and visit different parts of Europe."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit extends pupils’ knowledge of place by exploring the diversity of landscapes, climates and human features across Europe. Its placement builds on earlier UK-focused studies and prepares pupils to make comparisons with specific European regions in later units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the location of the continents.
Knowledge of the position and significance of key lines of latitude and longitude.
Knowledge of the diversity of physical and human geography at a continental scale.""" ;
  curric:id "285"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.721109Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-2 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-europe-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

